04735nam a22007455i 9780231511384DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20092009nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2009017741  a(OCoLC)1013953039  a97802315113847 a10.7312/finc139462doi  a(DE-B1597)458847  a(OCoLC)979831921  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aGT497.M4bF56 2010 7aREL0930002bisacsh04a974.4/022221 aFinch, Martha, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDissenting Bodies :bCorporealities in Early New England /cMartha Finch. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (296 p.) :b9 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: Embodying Godliness -- t1. Massasoit’s Stool and Wituwamat’s Head: Body Encounters -- t2. A Banquet in the Wilderness: Bodies and the Environment -- t3. As on a Hill: Public Bodies -- t4. The True and Visible Church: The Body of Christ -- t5. As in a Mirror: Domestic Bodies -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor the Puritan separatists of seventeenth-century New England, "godliness," as manifested by the body, was the sign of election, and the body, with its material demands and metaphorical significance, became the axis upon which all colonial activity and religious meaning turned. Drawing on literature, documents, and critical studies of embodiment as practiced in the New England colonies, Martha L. Finch launches a fascinating investigation into the scientific, theological, and cultural conceptions of corporeality at a pivotal moment in Anglo-Protestant history. Not only were settlers forced to interact bodily with native populations and other "new world" communities, they also fought starvation and illness; were whipped, branded, hanged, and murdered; sang, prayed, and preached; engaged in sexual relations; and were baptized according to their faith. All these activities shaped the colonists' understanding of their existence and the godly principles of their young society. Finch focuses specifically on Plymouth Colony and those who endeavored to make visible what they believed to be God's divine will. Quakers, Indians, and others challenged these beliefs, and the constant struggle to survive, build cohesive communities, and regulate behavior forced further adjustments. Merging theological, medical, and other positions on corporeality with testimonies on colonial life, Finch brilliantly complicates our encounter with early Puritan New England.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aBritish AmericanszMassachusettsxHistoryy17th century. 0aCommunity lifezMassachusettsxHistoryy17th century. 0aHuman bodyxSocial aspectszMassachusettsxHistoryy17th century. 0aHuman bodyzMassachusettsxReligious aspectsxHistoryy17th century. 0aMassachusetts - Race relations - History - 17th century. 0aPilgrims (New Plymouth Colony)xSocial life and customs. 0aProtestantszMassachusettsxHistoryy17th century. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Calvinist.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247240uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/finc1394640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231511384423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231511384/original  a978-3-11-044247-2  Columbia University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5